expression.value:
let requestType = raa_response.messageHeader.requestType,
    actionCode = !raa_response.success
        ? "DENY"
        : (
            raa_response.messageHeader.requestType == "ANALYZE" 
            ? (
                raa_response.riskResult.triggeredRule != null 
                ? (
                    raa_response.riskResult.triggeredRule.actionCode == "REDIRECT_CHALLENGE" 
                    ? "CHALLENGE" 
                    : raa_response.riskResult.triggeredRule.actionCode
                ) 
                : "ALLOW"
            ) 
            : (
                raa_response.credentialAuthResultList.challengeQuestionAuthResult.payload.challengeQuestionMatchResult.wasSuccessful == "true"
                ? "ALLOW" 
                : (
                    final_attempt
                    ? "DENY" 
                    : "CHALLENGE"
                )
            )
        )
return {
    "raaRequestType": requestType,
    "raaActionCode": actionCode
}

phoneRiskTransactionId.description: This is a unique id for all calls to Boku in one transaction.  Note that one transaction may be multiple steps, and a customer may need to complete a phone risk process  multiple times, each time being a separate transaction.

confidenceScore.description: This score indicates the level of confidence Boku has for the phone number. The score ranges from 0 - 100. A higher score indicates higher confidence. The confidence score considers all the attributes configured for the merchant at the time of onboarding.    Example: confidenceScore: 50

phoneNumber.description: The phone number on which the risk assessment is performed. It should in E.164 international format.      Example: +14085551234

serviceType.description: Indicates if the phone number is a mobile, fixed or VOIP. Example serviceType: mobile

countryPhoneCode.description: The unique number given to each country for dialing a Telephone Number in that country from abroad. e.g. 1 (USA) e.g. 32 (Belgium) e.g. 353 (Ireland) e.g. 44 (UK)

serviceProvider.description: Specifies the name of the carrier the phone number is registered to. Example serviceProvider: AT&T Wireless

streetAddressScore.description: Level of match for the Street Address attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.      The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *5= Partial Match   *9=High Partial Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

lastNameScore.description: Level of match for the Last Name attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.      The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *5= Partial Match   *9=High Partial Match   *10=Exact Match   Example lastNameScore: 10

emailAddressScore.description: Level of match for the Email Address attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

cityScore.description: Level of match for the City attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

zipCodeScore.description: Level of match for the Postal Codeattribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

dataSourceForVerification.description: Returns the data source that the merchant data was compared against. Values can be Carrier or Third-Party . Example dataSource: Carrier

firstNameScore.description: Level of match for the First Name attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match. The Values could be: -2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute -1=Data not available for attribute 0=No Match 5= Partial Match 9=High Partial Match 10=Exact Match Example firstNameScore: 10

stateScore.description: Level of match for the State attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

let rsaStageId = @namedContainers.namedStringListLookup("mae_raa_result_stageid_map", `${raa_request_type}_${raa_action_code}`, ""),
    rsaRiskScore = raa_response.riskResult == null ? "" : raa_response.riskResult.riskScore,
    finalResult = raa_response.success ? "SUCCESS" : "FAILURE",
    challengeType = raa_response.success && raa_request_type == "AUTHENTICATE" ? "SCQ" : "",
    userFailureReason = (raa_action_code == "DENY" || !raa_response.success) ? "RSA DENY" : "",
    failedAttempts = raa_response.success && raa_request_type == "AUTHENTICATE" 
                     ? raa_response.credentialAuthResultList.challengeQuestionAuthResult.payload.challengeQuestionMatchResult.failCount
                     : "0",
    lockUser = raa_action_code == "DENY" && raa_response.success ? "regular" : "",
    rsaFailureCode = raa_action_code == "DENY" && raa_response.success ? raa_response.statusHeader.statusCode : "",
    rsaFailurePayload = raa_action_code == "DENY" && raa_response.success ? raa_response.faultString : "",
    rsaFailureMessage = raa_response.success ? "" : "Error or exception occurred"
return {
    "hrtCode": raa_hrt_code,

    "rsaRiskScore": rsaRiskScore,
    "finalResult": finalResult,
    "userName": username,

    "allowURL": allow_url,
    "challengeType": challengeType,
    "userFailureReason": userFailureReason,
    "failedAttempts": failedAttempts,
    "lockUser": lockUser,
    "rsaFailurePayload": rsaFailurePayload,

}

phoneRiskTransactionId.description: This is a unique id for all calls to Boku in one transaction.  Note that one transaction may be multiple steps, and a customer may need to complete a phone risk process  multiple times, each time being a separate transaction.

confidenceScore.description: This score indicates the level of confidence Boku has for the phone number. The score ranges from 0 - 100. A higher score indicates higher confidence. The confidence score considers all the attributes configured for the merchant at the time of onboarding.    Example: confidenceScore: 50

phoneNumber.description: The phone number on which the risk assessment is performed. It should in E.164 international format.      Example: +14085551234

serviceType.description: Indicates if the phone number is a mobile, fixed or VOIP. Example serviceType: mobile

countryPhoneCode.description: The unique number given to each country for dialing a Telephone Number in that country from abroad. e.g. 1 (USA) e.g. 32 (Belgium) e.g. 353 (Ireland) e.g. 44 (UK)

serviceProvider.description: Specifies the name of the carrier the phone number is registered to. Example serviceProvider: AT&T Wireless

streetAddressScore.description: Level of match for the Street Address attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.      The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *5= Partial Match   *9=High Partial Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

lastNameScore.description: Level of match for the Last Name attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.      The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *5= Partial Match   *9=High Partial Match   *10=Exact Match   Example lastNameScore: 10

emailAddressScore.description: Level of match for the Email Address attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

cityScore.description: Level of match for the City attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match.   The Values could be   *-2=Merchant did not submit data for attribute   *-1=Data not available for attribute   *0=No Match   *10=Exact Match   Example Score: 10

zipCodeScore.description: Level of match for the Postal Codeattribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high - the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match. dataSourceForVerification.description: Returns the data source that the merchant data was compared against. Values can be Carrier or Third-Party . Example dataSource: Carrier

firstNameScore.description: Level of match for the First Name attribute assigned to the submitted mobile number from low to high the higher the Match score, more accurate is the match. expression.value:
let range = (i, n) =>
  let loop = (loop, i, acc) =>
    i < n ? @(loop)(loop, i + 1, acc + [i]) : acc
  return @(loop)(loop, i, []) return

let tail = (xs) => @slice(xs, 1, @len(xs)) return

let integer = (x) => @typeof(x) == "number" && @math.round(x) == x return

let set_array = (loop, xs, p) =>
  let xs = @typeof(xs) == "array" ? xs : [], i = p[0], t = @(tail)(p) return
  let xs =  @len(xs) >= i ? xs : @map(@(range)(0, i + 1), (x) => xs[x]) return
  let x = xs[i] return
  @len(xs) >= i ? @splice(xs, i, 1, [@(loop)(loop, xs[i], t)]) : [] return

let set_object = (loop, o, p) =>
  let o = @typeof(o) == "object" ? o : {}, k = p[0], t = @(tail)(p) return
  let v = o[k] return
  o + @kv("" + k, @(loop)(loop, v, t)) return

let loop = (loop, o, p) =>
  (p == []) ? value :
  ((@(integer)(p[0])) ? @(set_array)(loop, o, p) :
  (@(set_object)(loop, o, p))) return
@(loop)(loop, object, path)
